Symmetric Encryption 

⸻

1. Core Definitions
	•	Cipher / Algorithm
Method used to encrypt and decrypt data
	•	Key
Secret value used by the algorithm
	•	Plaintext
Original readable message
	•	Ciphertext
Encrypted unreadable output

⸻

2. Symmetric Encryption (Main Concept)
	•	Same key is used for:
	•	Encryption
	•	Decryption

Plaintext + Key → Encrypt → Ciphertext  
Ciphertext + Same Key → Decrypt → Plaintext


⸻

3. Example Flow (Important)

Input:

TANGO HOTEL MIKE

Step 1 — Convert to ASCII → Hex

T  → 54
A  → 41
N  → 4E
G  → 47
O  → 4F
(space) → 20

Final:

54 41 4E 47 4F 20 48 4F 54 45 4C 20 4D 49 4B 45


⸻

Step 2 — Form AES Block (128-bit = 16 bytes)

54 41 4E 47
4F 20 48 4F
54 45 4C 20
4D 49 4B 45

→ This is called the state matrix (4×4)

⸻

Step 3 — AES Encryption Process

AES applies multiple rounds of:

1. SubBytes
	•	Replace each byte using lookup table (S-box)

2. ShiftRows
	•	Row 1 → no shift
	•	Row 2 → shift left by 1
	•	Row 3 → shift left by 2
	•	Row 4 → shift left by 3

3. MixColumns
	•	Mix values in each column mathematically

4. AddRoundKey
	•	XOR with key

⸻

Output:

Ciphertext (hex)
EB C2 03 3F ...


⸻

4. Block Cipher vs Stream Cipher

Block Cipher (AES)
	•	Works on fixed size blocks (128 bits)
	•	Example:

[TANGO HOTEL MIKE] → one block → encrypt


⸻

Stream Cipher
	•	Encrypts byte-by-byte

54 → encrypt
41 → encrypt
4E → encrypt
...


⸻

5. Important Algorithms

Old (Insecure)
	•	DES (56-bit key → broken)
	•	3DES (deprecated)

Modern (Secure)
	•	AES (128 / 192 / 256-bit)
	•	Blowfish / Twofish
	•	Camellia

⸻

6. Security Properties Achieved

Confidentiality
	•	Data cannot be read without key

Integrity
	•	Changes in ciphertext break decryption

Authenticity
	•	Only someone with key could send it

⸻

7. Major Limitation (Very Important)

Key Distribution Problem

For:
	•	2 users → 1 key
	•	3 users → 3 keys
	•	100 users → 4950 keys

Formula:

n(n - 1) / 2


⸻

8. Tools Used

GPG

gpg --symmetric file.txt
gpg --decrypt file.txt.gpg

OpenSSL

openssl aes-256-cbc -e -in file.txt -out enc
openssl aes-256-cbc -d -in enc -out file.txt

With stronger protection:

-pbkdf2 -iter 10000


⸻

9. Key Takeaways
	•	Symmetric encryption = fast and efficient
	•	Uses same secret key
	•	AES = current standard
	•	Works on binary/hex data (not raw text)
	•	Main problem = key sharing

⸻

10. One-line Summary

Text → ASCII → Hex → Block → AES rounds → Ciphertext (requires same key to decrypt)